snippet.textDisplay:
We only have one life, if Virginia and Edgar were happy together, then good for them. Was it because the girl was 13? She died at 24... This wasn't uncommon. The universe wanted her to have some semblance of happiness with a man she trusted before she died. Was it because she was his cousin? Yeah because apparently relationships with others worked out great for Edgar.

Neither of these people would have children. They had very little. They had each other. So whatever practical, logical reasoning behind the taboo of incest is completely without basis here.

Condemn the one good thing to happen to Edgar, I do not. Those poor things. He wrote his best work in the arms of this girl, when she was gone he didn't just move on. This wasn't a meaningless pairing.

You feel more comfortable with the idea of him going back to a woman who had betrayed him, and possibly had him killed than be with a woman who actually inspired him to live. I sincerely question you all on the basis of your sense of morality here.
